  <p>
    If you only memorize one thing to improve your Scrabble game, make it the 2-letter words. They are short, they are scoring 2-12 points each, and they unlock parallel play — the single highest-leverage scoring technique in the game. A player who knows all 107 two-letter words will beat a player who knows 20 of them, every single time, even if their vocabulary is otherwise identical.
  </p>

  <h2>Why 2-Letter Words Matter</h2>
  <p>
    Consider this board state: your opponent just played CATER. You have the tiles A and X in your rack. If you only know the common 2-letter words (OF, TO, IN, IS, IT, AT, BE, NO, ON), you have no play here. But if you know that AX is a valid Scrabble word, you can play the A parallel to CATER (forming AC, AT, AE — all valid) and the X next to the E (forming EX). That is a 14-point play with two tiles, on what would otherwise be a dead turn.
  </p>
  <p>
    Two-letter words also let you "hook" existing words: add an S to make CATS, an E to make CATER, a Y to make CATTY. Each hook is a small but cumulative advantage.
  </p>

  <h2>The Complete List</h2>
  <p>
