  <h2>Memorization Strategy</h2>
  <p>
    Trying to memorize 107 words all at once is overwhelming. Use this staged approach:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Week 1:</strong> Learn the high-value words that contain Q, X, Z, J — QI, AX, EX, OX, XI, XU, ZA, JO. These score 8-19 points each on a Double Letter square.</li>
    <li><strong>Week 2:</strong> Learn the common ones you don't already know — AE, AI, AW, AY, EF, EL, EM, EN, ER, ES, ET, HA, HE, HI, HO, ID, IF, IS, IT, MY, OE, OK, ON, OR, OW, OY, PA, PI, RE, SO, TA, TI, TO, UP, US, WE, YA, YE, YO.</li>
    <li><strong>Week 3:</strong> Learn the obscure but legitimate ones — AA, AB, AG, AL, AM, AN, AR, AS, AT, BE, BI, BO, BY, CH, DA, DE, DO, EA, ED, EH, FA, FE, GI, GO, HM, IN, IO, JA, KA, KI, KO, LA, LI, LO, MA, ME, MI, MM, MO, MU, NA, NE, NO, NU, OB, OD, OF, OH, OI, OM, OP, OS, OU, PE, PO, SH, SI, ST, TE, UG, UH, UM, UN, UR, UT, VE, WO, ZO.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    After three weeks, all 107 are second nature. Test yourself by typing 2 letters into <a href="/">WordForge</a> and verifying the word exists.
  </p>

  <h2>When to Play 2-Letter Words</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Parallel play:</strong> Place a 2-letter word alongside an existing word to score both your new word and the cross-word.</li>
    <li><strong>Hook:</strong> Add a single letter to an existing word (CAT → CATE, CATER, CATTY).</li>
    <li><strong>Bonus square fishing:</strong> Drop a 2-letter word on a Double Letter or Triple Letter square for cheap points.</li>
    <li><strong>Endgame:</strong> When the bag is empty and you have a few tiles left, 2-letter words let you play out faster.</li>
  </ul>

